---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import LeadForm from '../components/LeadForm.astro';

const phone = "(801) 514-7004";
const phoneHref = "tel:+18015147004";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Roof Insurance Claims in Utah | Sandy Roofing Pros — Sandy, UT"
  description="How the roof damage insurance claim process works in Utah. What qualifies, how to file, why timing matters, and how Sandy Roofing Pros helps Salt Lake County homeowners navigate it."
  canonicalUrl="/insurance-claims"
>

  <section class="page-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <h1>Roof Damage Insurance Claims — What Utah Homeowners Need to Know</h1>
      <p>
        Filing a storm damage claim for your roof is more time-sensitive than most
        homeowners realize. Here's how the process works — and how to protect yourself.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- What Qualifies -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div style="max-width:820px; margin:0 auto;">

        <div class="section-heading" style="text-align:left; margin-bottom:2rem;">
          <span class="section-heading__eyebrow">Section 1</span>
          <h2>What Qualifies for an Insurance Claim</h2>
        </div>
        <p>
          Standard homeowner's insurance in Utah covers sudden, accidental damage caused
          by storms — hail, wind, lightning, and falling debris. The key phrase insurers
          use is <strong>"sudden and accidental."</strong> If a hailstorm hits Sandy in
          July and damages your shingles, that qualifies. If your shingles are cracked
          because they're 22 years old and overdue for replacement, that does not.
        </p>
        <p>What's typically covered:</p>
        <ul style="padding-left:1.25rem; margin-bottom:1.25rem; color:#64748B; line-height:1.85;">
          <li>Hail damage to shingles, gutters, and flashing</li>
          <li>Wind damage — missing or lifted shingles, damaged ridge caps</li>
          <li>Impact from fallen tree branches or debris</li>
          <li>Ice dam damage (varies by policy — check yours)</li>
        </ul>
        <p>What typically isn't:</p>
        <ul style="padding-left:1.25rem; margin-bottom:1.5rem; color:#64748B; line-height:1.85;">
          <li>Gradual deterioration and general wear</li>
          <li>Damage from deferred maintenance</li>
          <li>Pre-existing damage that predates the storm event</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          When in doubt, get an inspection. A licensed contractor can tell you whether
          what's on your roof reads as storm damage or wear — before you spend any time
          on a claim that won't go anywhere.
        </p>

        <hr style="border:none; border-top:1px solid #E2E8F0; margin:3rem 0;" />

        <div class="section-heading" style="text-align:left; margin-bottom:2rem;">
          <span class="section-heading__eyebrow">Section 2</span>
          <h2>How to File a Storm Damage Claim</h2>
        </div>
        <p>
          Most homeowners get this backwards. They call their insurance company first,
          an adjuster comes out, and without independent documentation, the claim gets
          underpaid. Here's the order that protects you:
        </p>

        <ol style="padding-left:1.5rem; color:#64748B; line-height:2; margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
          <li>
            <strong style="color:#1E293B;">Get an independent roof inspection first.</strong>
            A licensed contractor documents the damage with photos, measurements, and a
            written report — before your insurance company sends anyone out.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong style="color:#1E293B;">Call your insurer and open a claim.</strong>
            Reference the storm date and describe the damage. They'll assign an adjuster
            and schedule a visit.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong style="color:#1E293B;">Have your contractor present during the adjuster visit.</strong>
            Your documentation and your contractor's presence ensure nothing gets missed
            or minimized.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong style="color:#1E293B;">Review the settlement estimate carefully.</strong>
            Compare it to your contractor's assessment before signing anything. If there's
            a significant gap, you have grounds to dispute.
          </li>
        </ol>

        <hr style="border:none; border-top:1px solid #E2E8F0; margin:3rem 0;" />

        <div class="section-heading" style="text-align:left; margin-bottom:2rem;">
          <span class="section-heading__eyebrow">Section 3</span>
          <h2>Why Timing Matters More Than You Think</h2>
        </div>
        <p>
          Utah insurers generally give you up to 12 months from the storm date to file —
          but most roofing contractors and public adjusters recommend acting within
          30 to 60 days. Here's why:
        </p>
        <ul style="padding-left:1.25rem; margin-bottom:1.25rem; color:#64748B; line-height:1.85;">
          <li>
            Weather continues to cause additional damage that complicates what was
            caused by the storm versus what happened afterward
          </li>
          <li>
            Insurance companies match claims against weather data by date — the sooner
            you file, the cleaner the data match for your storm event
          </li>
          <li>
            Some policies have language that limits coverage if "known damage was not
            reported promptly"
          </li>
          <li>
            After a widespread storm event, contractor backlogs grow fast — early movers
            get earlier inspection dates
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Don't wait for it to leak. A roof that's leaking has almost certainly been
          compromised for longer than you realize — and the interior damage that follows
          is a separate claim problem you didn't need.
        </p>

        <hr style="border:none; border-top:1px solid #E2E8F0; margin:3rem 0;" />

        <div class="section-heading" style="text-align:left; margin-bottom:2rem;">
          <span class="section-heading__eyebrow">Section 4</span>
          <h2>How We Help</h2>
        </div>
        <p>
          We connect Salt Lake County homeowners with licensed roofing contractors who
          handle insurance claims every day. They know what adjusters look for, how to
          build a damage report that holds up, and how to represent your interests during
          the on-site inspection.
        </p>
        <p>
          You're not navigating this alone. Get an inspection on the books — it costs
          you nothing and gives you a clear picture of what you're dealing with before
          you make any decisions.
        </p>

        <div style="background:#FEF2F2; border:1px solid #FECACA; border-left:4px solid #B91C1C; border-radius:6px; padding:1.5rem 1.75rem; margin-top:2rem;">
          <p style="color:#7F1D1D; font-weight:700; margin-bottom:0.5rem;">
            Storm just hit your neighborhood?
          </p>
          <p style="color:#7F1D1D; margin-bottom:1rem;">
            Don't wait. Call us now or fill out the form below — a local contractor
            will follow up fast and get an inspection on the books.
          </p>
          <a href={phoneHref} class="btn btn--primary">📞 Call {phone}</a>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Lead Form -->
  <section class="section section--alt">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <span class="section-heading__eyebrow">Free Inspection</span>
        <h2>Get a Contractor Out Before You Call Your Insurer</h2>
        <p>Free, no obligation. A licensed Salt Lake County roofer will follow up fast.</p>
      </div>
      <LeadForm
        title="Request a Free Damage Inspection"
        subtitle="Our contractors document everything you need for a successful insurance claim."
        elementId="insurance-form"
      />
    </div>
  </section>

</BaseLayout>
